@tfirstelizabeth @jam__ie_ @TIFFANXx0 I know, but a lot of the healthy vegan foods involve imports - the cost of production has been placed on another country AND involve transport.

Sustainable food needs to take into account all of that. Local beef/lamb/venison can potentially be less impact than S. American soy.

The more animals we have eating grain the more it supports grain bids in general.

content:
@KetoSustainable @SteakAndIron @B_Holmer I hate to sound like a steak snob, but...
I think well raised beef is worth the extra cost. Even if it means going without other things or eating less of it.
I would like to see intensive beef production like in U.S. phased out.
I don't know if that's possible.

content:
In today's prices, an average pound of ground beef would cost $68. A loaf of bread would be $33.

Working class wages rose by only 8-10x by 1921, followed by smaller professional salaries at 2-4x. 

In other words, if this is your concern, own the means of production for food.
renderedContent:
In today's prices, an average pound of ground beef would cost $68. A loaf of bread would be $33.

Working class wages rose by only 8-10x by 1921, followed by smaller professional salaries at 2-4x. 

In other words, if this is your concern, own the means of production for food.

content:
Cultured meats

Cultured meats bring technologies developed over the last few decades in cell culture to food production. In 2013, the Post Lab at Maastricht University developed the first cultured meat product - a beef hamburger patty that cost around $300,000.

content: @DowlingWildlife My point would have continued to say that in the UK the highest climate impact food in terms of feed demand and waste etc is probably chicken. Free range costs more but more free range production will lower unit cost. Beef, pork and lamb can be completely regenerative.

content:
1 kilo of beef costs ~R44
Assuming the agricultural cost of water is still ~R7 per kL then the price water (R112) used in beef production is >> than the price of beef itself.
 
So I suspect the price of agricultural water is way more underpriced. 

Possibly less than R3 per KL https://t.co/lNIgYKVPmh

content:
Advantages of Rearing Goats over Cattle

1. Strong market and demand- goat meat is in high demand and has more value per kg that beef.
2. Goats are low cost to buy and rear
3. Shorter production cycles means quick return on investment https://t.co/ajZsG2MVPU

content:
Most of a food's carbon cost comes not from its production emissions, but the opportunity cost from producing farmland at the expense of wild habitats which could otherwise be restored. In total:

1kg soy protein = 17kg CO2e
1kg beef protein = 1250kg CO2e
https://t.co/F930eS8RMy https://t.co/E82DBkotxn

content:
@sedaliafarmer Yes, consumer demand is an unknown.
People still must eat, so I'm expecting domestic demand to remain stable.
Export demand may fluctuate.
Labour component of the cost-of-production of beef is in the meatworks.
IF labour costs move higher = beef prices will find a new price point

content:
Why don't lower standards matter to Ireland?

Because our agricultural production costs on beef are higher than Ireland's.

Even with lower standards, which we're not planning to do anyway, Ireland could still compete on cost.

British beef cannot compete effectively anywhere.

content:
@eat_more_tacos The poor need good balanced diets.
We should consider subsidies on fresh veggies & the like.
But beef?
No. People eat too much meat.
Should be priced according to the actual cost.
That will also encourage more environmentally friendly production.
Everyone should eat more veggies.

content:
@EthanolRFA Misleading 2:
One can argue RVO cost is mostly reflected in ref cracks, but that does not guarantee refiners can garner it. To do so, they must attain various RINs in sync with actually daily production and increase staff.  LR's do have a valid beef since SR's get an advantage.
renderedContent:
@EthanolRFA Misleading 2:
One can argue RVO cost is mostly reflected in ref cracks, but that does not guarantee refiners can garner it. To do so, they must attain various RINs in sync with actually daily production and increase staff.  LR's do have a valid beef since SR's get an advantage.

Did you know? 
-@McDonalds buys 2% of the worlds beef volume

content: Unless you farm a couple million acres or more you are still a price taker. Big Corp sets your commodity price, whether sugar, corn, soybeans, wheat, sorghum, cotton, dairy, or beef, not the farmer.  When your cost of production goes up, you can't pass it on.
